A member of a UN investigation team takes samples of sands near a part of a missile likely to be one of the chemical rockets. (Picture: AP) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories "The use of these weapons in Syria... is wholly unacceptable by any standard," spokesperson Clayson Monyela said in a statement."No cause could ever justify the use of weapons of mass destruction."He said the UN weapons inspectors should be allowed the time to complete their investigation and announce their findings.AFP reported on Thursday that the inspectors were heading to one of the sites near Damascus where Syria's government allegedly attacked civilians with poisonous gas.The UN team was on its third day of inspections. UN Secretary General Ban Ki-moon reportedly said they would need four days to conclude the probe.Monyela said SA was concerned about the continuing violence and deteriorating human rights situation in Syria.The country was also worried about the "dangerous rhetoric" referring to possible military intervention."South Africa does not believe that bombing the already suffering people and crumbling infrastructure of Syria will contribute to a sustainable solution," he said."The outcome of such an action is unpredictable and will only worsen the conflict."The South African government called on all those involved in the conflict in Syria to engage in non-violent processes."We, therefore, call on the members of the UN Security Council to unite in purpose in moving the parties to a negotiated settlement," Monyela said.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.